Manuel Pellegrini seems to be tapering Aguero's return to first team action as he nurses the injury-prone forward back to full fitness after a busy summer which saw Argentina reach the World Cup final in Brazil.

Pellegrini's decision to use Aguero from the bench for the first two Premier League games of the season looks to be a wise one as the former Atletico Madrid man has knotched against Newcastle and Liverpool. 

If Aguero can carry on at the scoring rate, there's no doubt that he'll beat his goalscoring record of the 2013/14 Premier League season which saw the diminutive striker score 15 goals in 23 league appearance for City. 

Aguero knocked Arsenal legend Thierry Henry off the top of the list as his record pips the Frenchman's stunning return of 175 goals every 122 Premier League minutes.

